style="vertical-align:top;"><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;font-style:italic;">$42 million of net loan growth, including run-off from purchased loans</font></div></td></tr></table><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;padding-left:72px;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;font-weight:bold;">ATLANTA, GA, </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;font-weight:bold;">July&#160;23, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;- State Bank Financial Corporation (NASDAQ: STBZ) today announced unaudited financial results for the quarter ended </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">.  After incorporating our previously disclosed one-time pre-tax charge of $14.5 million that resulted from the early termination of our loss share agreements, net loss for the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;was $2.0 million, compared to net income of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">$7.5 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;for the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2014</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;and net income of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">$9.2 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;for the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">.  Fully diluted loss per share was $.06 in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;compared to fully diluted earnings per share of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">$.22</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2014</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;and fully diluted earnings per share of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">$.25</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">.  On an operating basis, income for the second quarter of 2015 was $7.7 million, or $.20 per fully diluted share. </font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">Joe Evans, Chairman and CEO, commented, "The big event of the second quarter was the early termination of our FDIC loss share agreements with a related one-time charge that led to negative earnings.  I am extremely pleased to have accomplished early termination and remain highly confident that the financial benefits will allow us to recover this charge within five quarters as we previously announced.  We continue to experience strong organic loan and noninterest-bearing deposit growth and reap the benefits of our focus on key noninterest income initiatives.&#160; These fundamentals produced another quarter of solid operating results with strong momentum carrying over into the second half of the year."</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;font-weight:bold;">Operating Highlights</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">Net interest income of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$33.5 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;decreased from </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$39.1 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;due to lower accretion income on loans, but increased from $33.1 million in the second quarter of 2014.  Interest income on loans, excluding purchased credit impaired loans, for the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$23.1 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">up</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;$1.7 million from </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$21.4 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;in the prior quarter and up $7.8 million from $15.4 million in the second quarter of 2014.  Accretion income on loans was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$8.4 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">down</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;from </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$16.1 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;due primarily to larger gains from early loan payoffs in the previous quarter as well as a loan pool that closed out in the first quarter of 2015.  Base accretion declined $1.3 million in the second quarter of 2015 compared to the </font></div><br><div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><a name="s164F78B0E49E4D66E30B48B6BEEC8CAF"></a><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><br><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">prior quarter.   As of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">June 30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, approximately $104 million of accretable discount remains to be recognized as loan accretion income, compared to $110 million of accretable discount remaining at the end of the first quarter of 2015.  Interest expense of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$2.0 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;was essentially flat compared to the prior quarter.  Cost of funds for the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">29</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;basis points, </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">unchanged</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;from the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;and down six basis points from the second quarter of 2014.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">The organic loan portfolio continued to perform well in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;as past due organic loans represented only .08% of total organic loans.  The provision for loan losses was $64 thousand in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, a decrease of $3.1 million compared to the first quarter of 2015, of which $2.3 million was related to purchased credit impaired loans.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">Noninterest income, excluding (amortization)/accretion of the FDIC receivable for loss share agreements, was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$9.3 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;for the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, compared to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$10.3 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">.  The </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;included $380 thousand in securities gains and $2.0 million in prepayment fees. In the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, we continued to experience solid growth in our noninterest income key initiatives as income from mortgage banking of $3.5 million and SBA lending of $1.4 million were up $800 thousand and $257 thousand, respectively, from the previous quarter.  Payroll fee income of $956 thousand increased versus the prior year period, but was down from the previous quarter due to what is typically a seasonally strong first quarter.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">On May 21, 2015, State Bank entered into an agreement with the FDIC to terminate the loss share agreements on all 12 FDIC-assisted acquisitions that occurred in 2009, 2010 and 2011, resulting in a pre-tax charge of approximately $14.5 million for the second quarter of 2015.  Approximately $9.3 million of the one-time pre-tax charge was related to amortization scheduled to be recognized during future quarters, with the remainder primarily consisting of the payment made to the FDIC to eliminate all rights and obligations between State Bank and the FDIC, most significantly the elimination of the FDIC's right to share in the recovery of losses previously recognized under loss share.  State Bank will now retain 100% of future recoveries instead of retaining either 5% or 20% of future recoveries as provided in the now terminated loss share agreements.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">Total noninterest expense for the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;was </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$31.4 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, a $1.3 million increase from</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">the first quarter of 2015, due primarily to higher merger-related expenses and salary and benefit costs largely as a result of severance related to the early termination of loss share.  Merger-related expenses totaled $876 thousand in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, up from $137 thousand in the first quarter of 2015.  Severance expenses totaled $443 thousand in the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, compared to $365 thousand in the first quarter of 2015.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;font-weight:bold;">Financial Condition</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">Total assets at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;were </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">$3.3 billion</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;but up from </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$2.6 billion</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">June&#160;30, 2014</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">.  Period-end organic loans increased to $1.5 billion at </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">June&#160;30, 2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, a net increase of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$90.8 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;from the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;and </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$294.0 million</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;from the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of 2014.  Approximately $10.5 million of the growth in organic loans was related to loan renewals of purchased non-credit impaired loans that migrated into organic loans.  Purchased non-credit impaired loans decreased $35.3 million from the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;to $340.5 million, and purchased credit impaired loans decreased to $177.4 million at the end of the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">, a $13.5 million linked-quarter decline.  Total net loans, excluding loans held for sale, were </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">$2.0 billion</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">.</font></div><br><div style="text-align:center;"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font Average transaction accounts, comprised of noninterest-bearing demand deposits and interest-bearing transaction accounts, increased $105.7 million from the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">first</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">Tangible book value per share was </font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:12pt;color:#000000;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;text-decoration:none;">$13.51</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;at the end of the </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">second</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#32;quarter of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">2015</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">.  State Bank Financial Corporation continues to be well capitalized, ending the quarter with </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">a leverage ratio of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">14.78</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">% and a Tier I risk-based capital ratio of </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">18.83</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;">%.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0d0d0d;font-weight:bold;">Branch Closures</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">As part of our ongoing strategy to deploy personnel and resources more efficiently, State Bank consolidated three branch offices in Middle Georgia in the second quarter of 2015.  After completing the First Bank of Georgia conversion, which is scheduled for the weekend of July 25-26, 2015, State Bank will operate 26 banking offices in three primary markets: Metro Atlanta (7), Middle Georgia (12), and Augusta (7), as well as five mortgage origination offices in the Atlanta, Augusta and Savannah, Georgia markets.</font></div><div As of June 30, 2015, State Bank operated 19 banking offices in Metro Atlanta and Middle Georgia and one mortgage origination office in metro Atlanta.  First Bank of Georgia operated seven banking offices and four mortgage origination offices in the Augusta and Savannah, Georgia MSAs.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">&#160;</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;">To learn more about State Bank, visit </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;color:#0000ff;text-decoration:underline;">www.statebt.com</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Cautionary Note Regarding Forward-Looking Statements</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:left;font-size:12pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:12pt;font-style:italic;">Certain statements on our conference call may be "forward-looking statements&#8221; within the meaning of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995. Forward-looking statements can be identified by words such as: &#8220;intend,&#8221; &#8220;plan,&#8221; &#8220;seek,&#8221; &#8220;believe,&#8221; &#8220;expect,&#8221; &#8220;strategy,&#8221; &#8220;future,&#8221; &#8220;likely,&#8221; &#8220;project,&#8221; &#8220;may,&#8221; &#8220;should,&#8221; &#8220;will&#8221; and similar references to future periods.  Examples of forward-looking statements include, among others, the expected future financial benefits of our early termination of loss share coverage and our operating momentum carrying into the second half of 2015.  Such forward-looking statements are subject to risks, uncertainties, and other factors, such as a downturn in the economy, unanticipated losses related to the integration of, and accounting for, acquired assets and assumed liabilities in our acquisitions, access to funding sources, greater than expected noninterest expenses, volatile credit and financial markets both domestic and foreign, potential deterioration in real estate values, regulatory changes and excessive loan losses, any or all of which could cause actual results to differ materially from future results expressed or implied by such forward-looking statements. Although we believe that the assumptions underlying the forward-looking statements are reasonable, any of the assumptions could prove to be inaccurate. Therefore, we can give no assurance that the results contemplated in the forward-looking statements will be realized. The inclusion of this forward-looking information should not be construed as a representation by our company or any person that future events, plans, or expectations contemplated by our company will be achieved. We undertake no obligation to publicly update or revise any forward-looking statements, whether as a result of new information, future events, or otherwise. See Item 1A, Risk Factors, in our Annual Report on Form 10-K for the most recently ended fiscal year, for a description of some of the important factors that may affect actual style="font-family:inherit;font-size:9pt;">(1) Management evaluates the capital position and operating performance of State Bank Financial Corporation (the &#8220;Company&#8221;) by using certain financial measures not calculated in accordance with U.S. Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (&#8220;GAAP&#8221;), including:  interest income - taxable equivalent, net interest income - taxable equivalent, (amortization) accretion of FDIC receivable for loss share agreements, operating income before taxes - taxable equivalent, income tax expense, and tangible book value per common share.  The Company has included these non-GAAP financial measures in this press release for the applicable periods presented.  Management believes that the presentation of these non-GAAP financial measures (a)&#160;provides important supplemental information that contributes to a proper understanding of the Company&#8217;s operating performance, (b)&#160;enables a more complete understanding of factors and trends affecting the Company&#8217;s business, and (c)&#160;allows investors to evaluate the Company&#8217;s performance in a manner similar to management, the financial services industry, bank stock analysts, and bank regulators.  Management uses non-GAAP measures as follows: preparation of the Company&#8217;s operating budgets, monthly financial performance reporting, and presentation to investors of Company performance.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:16px;text-align:left;padding-left:18px;font-size:9pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:9pt;">Reconciliations of these non-GAAP financial measures to the most directly comparable GAAP financial measures are presented in the accompanying table.  Non-GAAP financial measures have inherent limitations, are not required to be uniformly applied, and are not audited.  These non-GAAP financial measures should not be considered as substitutes for GAAP financial measures, and the Company strongly encourages investors to review the GAAP financial measures included in this press release and not to place undue reliance upon any single financial measure.  In addition, because non-GAAP financial measures are not standardized, it may not be possible to compare the non-GAAP financial measures presented in this press release with other companies&#8217; non-GAAP financial measures having the same or similar names. </font></div><br><div style="text-align:center;"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font <DIV><FONT size="1" style="font-size:1pt;color:white">3   Notes: Consolidated financial results for 2Q 2015 contained throughout this presentation are unaudited; numbers may not add due to rounding.                Includes certain financial information determined by methods other than in accordance with GAAP (for more information, refer to Table 2 on page 7 of the corresponding press release).   2Q15 Results Summary   &#61607; 2Q15 net loss of $2.0 million,   due to one-time after-tax   charge of $8.9 million related   to early termination of loss   share agreements   &#61607; 2Q15 operating income of   $7.7 million, or $.20 per   diluted share   &#61607; Continued growth in key   noninterest income initiatives   &#61607; Total loan growth of $42   million during 2Q15,   including purchased loan    run-off   &#61607; Noninterest-bearing deposits   comprise nearly 28% of total   deposits   &#61607;
